<subSubSection lastPageId="48" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1437,1791,2034]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,328,1791,1818]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Type Material.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="2857124537" collectionCode="ZMB" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" specimenCode="ZMB 408" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="lectotype">
The 
<typeStatus box="[384,487,1792,1818]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1860" box="[523,761,1792,1818]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Chiroderma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="villosum">
<emphasis box="[523,761,1792,1818]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Chiroderma villosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<specimenCode box="[775,890,1792,1818]" collectionCode="ZMB" country="Germany" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/8syf-d21i" name="Museum für Naturkunde Berlin (Zoological Collections)" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="Museum">ZMB 408</specimenCode>
), designated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, O." box="[1069,1244,1792,1818]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" pagination="881 - 883" refId="ref48200" refString="Thomas, O. (1891) Note on Chiroderma villosum with the description of a new species for the genus. Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Genova, Series 2, 10, 881 - 883." type="journal article" year="1891">Thomas (1891)</bibRefCitation>
, is a stuffed skin. The skull is inside the skin and the skin around the lips is everted, exposing all of the teeth except M2 and m2.
</materialsCitation>
The free portion of the noseleaf spear is broken. The wing patagia are crumbly and several fragments have fallen off. The tips of the ears are also crumbly. The skin appears to preserve the original color, the interocular stripes are barely visible, but the genal pair is not visible. Dorsal pelage is pale brown and three bands can be distinguished: a dark brown base, and buff middle. The dorsal stripe appears to be lacking.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1437,1791,2034]" lastBlockId="48.[151,1437,153,323]" lastPageId="48" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
The I1s are parallel to each other, not in contact, and have slightly diverging tips. The p2 is small and clearly separated from p4. The forearm measures 
<quantity box="[621,724,153,179]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.79" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" unit="mm" value="47.9">47.9 mm</quantity>
. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, O." box="[885,1059,153,179]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" pagination="881 - 883" refId="ref48200" refString="Thomas, O. (1891) Note on Chiroderma villosum with the description of a new species for the genus. Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Genova, Series 2, 10, 881 - 883." type="journal article" year="1891">Thomas (1891)</bibRefCitation>
, the individual depicted in Peters’ (1906) plate, published posthumously, is probably the 
<typeStatus box="[770,822,189,215]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">type</typeStatus>
. In the illustration, the skull is separate from the skin, suggesting that the skull could have been removed and later re-inserted in the skin (
<figureCitation box="[1098,1182,225,251]" captionStart="FIGURE 31" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1187,1212]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,345,1162]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[189,1398,345,1162]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 31. Plate of the lectotype of Chiroderma villosum by Wilhelm Peters, published posthumously." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4017559" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4017559/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
). The other possibility is that the skull Peters illustrated belonged to the partial skeleton referred to, but not examined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Carter, D. C. &amp; Dolan, P. G." pageId="48" pageNumber="49" pagination="1 - 136" refId="ref39338" refString="Carter, D. C. &amp; Dolan, P. G. (1978) Catalogue of type specimens of neotropical bats in selected european museums. Museum of Texas Tech University Special Publications 15. Museum of Texas Tech University Press, Lubbock, Texas, pp. 1 - 136." type="book chapter" year="1978">Carter &amp; Dolan (1978:59)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4017559" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4017559" box="[151,1216,1187,1212]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4017559/files/figure.png" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" startId="48.[151,250,1187,1212]" targetBox="[189,1398,345,1162]" targetPageId="48">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1216,1187,1212]" box="[151,1216,1187,1212]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,288,1187,1212]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">FIGURE 31.</emphasis>
Plate of the lectotype of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1860" box="[542,758,1188,1212]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Chiroderma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="villosum">
<emphasis box="[542,758,1188,1212]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Chiroderma villosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Wilhelm Peters, published posthumously.
</paragraph>
</caption>
